subSection.paragraph:
Many new species of
Tylototriton
have been described in very recent years (e.g.,
Nishikawa et al . 2013 a
, b ;
Nishikawa et al . 2014
;
Le et al. 2015
). The genus is taxonomically difficult, and most newly described species have been differentiated on the basis of mitochondrial DNA sequence divergence, coloration in life, or size and shape differences (Stuart et al. 2010 ;
Nishikawa et al . 2013 a
, b ;
Nishikawa et al . 2014
;
Le et al. 2015
). Two of the most widely distributed species in the genus,
T. verrucosus
Anderson 1871
and
T. shanjing
Nussbaum, Brodie & Yang 1995
occur in parapatry (
Nussbaum et al. 1995
), and have shared mitochondrial genomes (
Zhang et al. 2007
), presumably from introgression, that further complicates the taxonomy of these taxa. There is consensus from previous analyses that the genus contains two major clades, corresponding to the subgenus
Tylototriton
Dubois & Raffaëlli 2009
(=
T. verrucosus
species group of
Fei et al. 2005
) and the subgenus Yaotriton
Dubois & Raffaëlli 2009
(=
T. asperrimus
species group of
Fei et al. 2005
), but species boundaries within each of these clades have been disputed (e.g,
Zhang et al. 2007
;
Yuan et al. 2011
;
Nishikawa et al. 2013 b
;
Zhang et al. 2013
;
Sparreboom 2014
; Nishikawa et al. 2015 ).

Partitioned Bayesian phylogenetic inference was performed with the mt DNA data using MrBayes 3.2 . 2 (
Ronquist et al . 2012
) on the Cyberinfrastructure for Phylogenetic Research (CIPRES) Science Gate Way v. 3.3 (
Miller et al. 2010
). The partitioning scheme and best models of sequence evolution for each partition were selected using PartitionFinder v1.1.0 (
Lanfear et al . 2012
). The selected models and partitions were TIM+G for 16 S rRNA; GTR+I+G for tRNA Ile , tRNA Leu, and tRNA Met; GTR+G for ND 1 first codon position; GTR+I+G for ND 1 second codon position; GTR+I+G for ND 1 third codon position; TrN+I+G for tRNA Gln and tRNA Trp; TIM+I+G for ND 2 first codon position; TIM+I+G for COI second codon position and ND 2 second codon position; GTR+I+G for ND 2 third codon position; TVM+G for tRNA Ala and tRNA Asn; SYM+G for tRNA Cys; TVMef+I+G for tRNA Tyr; and JC for COI first and third codon positions. Four independent Bayesian runs were performed. In each run, four chains ran for 20,000,000 generations using the default priors, the chain temperature was set to 0.1 , trees were sampled every 4,000 generations, and the first 25 % of trees were discarded as “burn in”.

Molecular analyses. The aligned dataset contained 3,121 characters. The standard deviation of split frequencies among the four Bayesian runs was 0.004936 and trace plots of clade probabilities viewed using AWTY (
Wilgenbusch et al. 2004
) were relatively stationary. This suggests that the four runs in each analysis had sufficiently converged and that topologies were sampled in proportion to their true posterior probability distribution.

